Backend-development, Stage-1 — questions raised while reviewing the business rules for API design, answered strictly from what's already locked in BUSINESS_RULES.md. Neither answer required a new business decision — both were already covered, just not phrased as an obvious "yes/no."

---

Q1. Won't the user get a notification when they order or cancel an item?

Two different things are easy to conflate here, so keep them separate:

1. Service-to-service: order-service publishes an `order.placed` /
   `order.cancelled` event to RabbitMQ, and notification-service consumes
   it (ARCHITECTURE.md §5). That's internal plumbing between two services
   — it is not what "notification" means in the business rules, and
   notification-service is not the notification's audience.
2. The actual notification (NTF-001/NTF-002): the record that gets
   created belongs to the buyer's account. NTF-001/002 are unconditional
   — placing an order always records an "order placed" notification "for
   that order's buyer," cancelling one always records "order cancelled"
   the same way. NTF-003 reinforces this: a notification "belongs to
   exactly one account and is visible only to that account." The user is
   the recipient, not another service — the record is never skipped.

What doesn't happen is delivery. NTF-004 is explicit and deliberate: this system records notifications as in-system, viewable history only. It does not send email, SMS, or push notifications through any outside channel, because the system has no outbound delivery capability — promising real delivery would be a rule the system couldn't keep. That's listed again in §8 (Explicitly out of scope) as "Real outbound delivery of notifications."

Practically: after Alice places an order, a row exists in notification-service the instant order-service's event is consumed (NTF-001) — but Alice only sees it if she calls GET /api/notifications herself. There is no push, no badge, no email hitting her inbox. So "the user gets notified" is true only in the passive, pull sense — a record they can look up — never in the active, push sense. If that's not the intended user experience, that's a new business requirement (a delivery channel), not something to infer or build around silently — see NTF-004's own [Decision] marker and §8.

