Q2. What happens when a deactivated user is activated again?

ACC-008 names reactivation directly: "Only an Administrator can deactivate or reactivate an account." So it's a defined action, not an implementation detail I'm inferring.

What it does, precisely, by chaining the rules that already exist:
- ACC-006: an account has exactly one status at all times, Active or Deactivated. Reactivating sets it back to Active — there's no third "reactivated" state to design for.
- ACC-007's restrictions (can't log in, can't place new orders) are conditioned on being Deactivated. Once status flips back to Active, those restrictions no longer apply — login and checkout work again, with no rule describing any additional gate (no re-verification, no cooldown, no forced password reset — the latter is out of scope entirely per §8, "Password reset / forgot password").
- Past order history was never touched by the deactivation in the first place (ACC-007, ORD-014), so reactivation has nothing to "restore" there — it was never hidden or altered.
- Role is untouched by this action. Deactivate/reactivate (ACC-008) and promote-to-Administrator (ACC-009) are separate, unrelated actions — reactivating a Customer does not change their role, and there's no rule suggesting it would.

One thing genuinely not covered, flagged rather than invented: no rule says reactivation fires a notification. NTF-001/002 only cover order placed/cancelled — reactivation isn't an order event, so by the locked rules it produces no notification. If the business wants the user to know they've been reactivated, that's new scope, not something to quietly add here.
